Note:
AArch64 NEON Vectorizer - SIMD Operations Using V Registers

Generates AArch64 NEON (Advanced SIMD) instructions for vectorized operations using
the 128-bit V0-V31 register file. NEON provides parallel computation on multiple
data elements packed into a single register.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Emits NEON arithmetic operations: add, sub, mul (element-wise)
- Emits NEON logical operations: and, orr, eor (bitwise on vectors)
- Emits NEON memory operations: ld1, st1 (vector load/store)
- Emits NEON broadcast operations: dup (replicate scalar to all lanes)
- Maps LIR vector opcodes to NEON instruction sequences
- Handles data arrangement specifiers (4S, 2D, 8H, 16B, etc.)

NEON data arrangements:
  128-bit (Q-form, full vector):
    16B = 16 x  8-bit bytes
    8H  =  8 x 16-bit halfwords
    4S  =  4 x 32-bit single-precision or integers
    2D  =  2 x 64-bit double-precision or integers

  64-bit (D-form, lower half only):
    8B  =  8 x  8-bit bytes
    4H  =  4 x 16-bit halfwords
    2S  =  2 x 32-bit
    1D  =  1 x 64-bit

NEON instruction syntax:
  add  v0.4s, v1.4s, v2.4s    -- 4x32-bit integer add
  fadd v0.4s, v1.4s, v2.4s    -- 4x32-bit float add
  fadd v0.2d, v1.2d, v2.2d    -- 2x64-bit float add
  and  v0.16b, v1.16b, v2.16b -- 128-bit bitwise AND
  ld1  {v0.4s}, [x0]          -- Load 128 bits into v0 as 4x32-bit
  st1  {v0.4s}, [x0]          -- Store 128 bits from v0
  dup  v0.4s, w0              -- Broadcast 32-bit GPR to all 4 lanes

Dependencies:
- Imports machine_code_interface.runa for output buffer types and section constants
- Imports calling_convention.runa for FPR register ID constants
- Imports layout.runa for memory allocation
- Imports list.runa for collection operations
- Imports string_utils.runa for integer-to-string conversion
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/aarch64/calling_convention.runa" as CallingConv
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Data Arrangement Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
NEON data arrangement specifiers control how many elements and what element size
a vector operation processes. These constants identify the arrangement for suffix
generation. The arrangement determines:
- The number of lanes (elements) in the vector
- The width of each lane
- Whether the operation uses the full 128-bit register or lower 64-bit half

The integer values are arbitrary identifiers used in the get_arrangement_suffix
lookup function.
@End Reasoning

Constant ARRANGEMENT_16B as Integer is 0    Note: 16 x  8-bit bytes (128-bit)
Constant ARRANGEMENT_8H as Integer is 1     Note:  8 x 16-bit halfwords (128-bit)
Constant ARRANGEMENT_4S as Integer is 2     Note:  4 x 32-bit words (128-bit)
Constant ARRANGEMENT_2D as Integer is 3     Note:  2 x 64-bit doublewords (128-bit)
Constant ARRANGEMENT_8B as Integer is 4     Note:  8 x  8-bit bytes (64-bit lower half)
Constant ARRANGEMENT_4H as Integer is 5     Note:  4 x 16-bit halfwords (64-bit lower half)
Constant ARRANGEMENT_2S as Integer is 6     Note:  2 x 32-bit words (64-bit lower half)
Constant ARRANGEMENT_1D as Integer is 7     Note:  1 x 64-bit doubleword (64-bit lower half)

Note: LIR vector operation opcodes are imported from the canonical definitions
Note: in compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa via the LIR import (X from LIR form).

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Arrangement Suffix Lookup
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the string suffix for the given data arrangement constant. This suffix is
appended to the register name in NEON instructions, e.g., v0.4s, v1.2d, v2.16b.

Each arrangement suffix encodes both the element count and element size, which the
assembler uses to determine the correct instruction encoding.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_arrangement_suffix" that takes arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_16B:
        Return ".16b"
    End If
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_8H:
        Return ".8h"
    End If
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_4S:
        Return ".4s"
    End If
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_2D:
        Return ".2d"
    End If
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_8B:
        Return ".8b"
    End If
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_4H:
        Return ".4h"
    End If
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_2S:
        Return ".2s"
    End If
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_1D:
        Return ".1d"
    End If
    Note: Default to 4S (32-bit words, most common for integer SIMD)
    Return ".4s"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NEON Register Name Helper
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the V register name with arrangement suffix for a given FPR register ID.
For example, register ID 32 (V0) with arrangement 4S returns "v0.4s".

The register name is built by combining the base V register name with the
arrangement suffix string.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_neon_reg_name" that takes reg_id as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fpr_index be reg_id minus 32
    If fpr_index is less than 0:
        Set fpr_index to 0
    End If
    If fpr_index is greater than 31:
        Set fpr_index to 0
    End If

    Let suffix be get_arrangement_suffix(arrangement)

    Note: Build "v<N><suffix>" string
    Let buf be Layout.allocate(16)
    Let pos be 0

    Note: Write 'v' prefix
    __store8(buf, pos, 118)  Note: 'v'
    Set pos to pos plus 1

    Note: Write register number
    Let num_str be StringUtils.integer_to_string(fpr_index)
    Let ni be 0
    Let nc be __load8(num_str, ni)
    While nc is not 0:
        __store8(buf, pos, nc)
        Set pos to pos plus 1
        Set ni to ni plus 1
        Set nc to __load8(num_str, ni)
    End While

    Note: Write arrangement suffix
    Let si be 0
    Let sc be __load8(suffix, si)
    While sc is not 0:
        __store8(buf, pos, sc)
        Set pos to pos plus 1
        Set si to si plus 1
        Set sc to __load8(suffix, si)
    End While

    __store8(buf, pos, 0)
    Return buf
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NEON Arithmetic Operations
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Emits a NEON integer ADD instruction: add Vd.<T>, Vn.<T>, Vm.<T>
where <T> is the data arrangement (4S, 2D, 8H, 16B, etc.).

For integer element sizes, the add instruction performs element-wise addition
across all lanes simultaneously. For example, add v0.4s, v1.4s, v2.4s adds
four 32-bit integers in parallel.

Parameters:
- output: pointer to AssemblyOutput buffer
- vd, vn, vm: FPR register IDs (32-63 mapping to V0-V31)
- arrangement: data arrangement constant (ARRANGEMENT_4S, ARRANGEMENT_2D, etc.)
@End Reasoning

Process called "emit_neon_add" that takes output as Integer, vd as Integer, vn as Integer, vm as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
    Let dest_str be get_neon_reg_name(vd, arrangement)
    Let src1_str be get_neon_reg_name(vn, arrangement)
    Let src2_str be get_neon_reg_name(vm, arrangement)

    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tadd\t")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Emits a NEON integer SUB instruction: sub Vd.<T>, Vn.<T>, Vm.<T>
Element-wise subtraction across all lanes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "emit_neon_sub" that takes output as Integer, vd as Integer, vn as Integer, vm as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
    Let dest_str be get_neon_reg_name(vd, arrangement)
    Let src1_str be get_neon_reg_name(vn, arrangement)
    Let src2_str be get_neon_reg_name(vm, arrangement)

    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tsub\t")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Emits a NEON integer MUL instruction: mul Vd.<T>, Vn.<T>, Vm.<T>
Element-wise multiplication (lower result) across all lanes.

Note: NEON integer MUL is only available for 8B/16B, 4H/8H, 2S/4S arrangements.
There is no 2D (64-bit element) integer multiply in NEON. For 2D integer multiply,
a sequence of UMULL/SMULL instructions would be needed, but this is rare in practice.
The caller is responsible for not requesting 2D integer multiply.
@End Reasoning

Process called "emit_neon_mul" that takes output as Integer, vd as Integer, vn as Integer, vm as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT

    Note: For floating-point arrangements, use fmul instead of mul
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_4S:
        Note: Could be integer or float - caller determines via separate functions
        Note: This function handles integer MUL
        Let dest_str be get_neon_reg_name(vd, arrangement)
        Let src1_str be get_neon_reg_name(vn, arrangement)
        Let src2_str be get_neon_reg_name(vm, arrangement)

        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tmul\t")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: All other valid arrangements (16B, 8H, 8B, 4H, 2S)
    Set dest_str to get_neon_reg_name(vd, arrangement)
    Set src1_str to get_neon_reg_name(vn, arrangement)
    Set src2_str to get_neon_reg_name(vm, arrangement)

    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tmul\t")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NEON Logical Operations
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
NEON bitwise operations operate on the full 128-bit register as a single bit vector.
The arrangement suffix for bitwise operations is always .16b (or .8b for 64-bit form)
because the operation is performed on all 128 bits regardless of element interpretation.
However, the assembler accepts any arrangement; .16b is canonical.
@End Reasoning

Process called "emit_neon_and" that takes output as Integer, vd as Integer, vn as Integer, vm as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
    Note: Bitwise AND always uses .16b arrangement for the full 128-bit register
    Let dest_str be get_neon_reg_name(vd, ARRANGEMENT_16B)
    Let src1_str be get_neon_reg_name(vn, ARRANGEMENT_16B)
    Let src2_str be get_neon_reg_name(vm, ARRANGEMENT_16B)

    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tand\t")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "emit_neon_or" that takes output as Integer, vd as Integer, vn as Integer, vm as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
    Let dest_str be get_neon_reg_name(vd, ARRANGEMENT_16B)
    Let src1_str be get_neon_reg_name(vn, ARRANGEMENT_16B)
    Let src2_str be get_neon_reg_name(vm, ARRANGEMENT_16B)

    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\torr\t")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "emit_neon_xor" that takes output as Integer, vd as Integer, vn as Integer, vm as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
    Let dest_str be get_neon_reg_name(vd, ARRANGEMENT_16B)
    Let src1_str be get_neon_reg_name(vn, ARRANGEMENT_16B)
    Let src2_str be get_neon_reg_name(vm, ARRANGEMENT_16B)

    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\teor\t")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NEON Memory Operations
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
NEON load/store uses LD1/ST1 for single-structure access (the most common form).
These instructions load/store a full vector register from/to a contiguous memory
address.

Syntax: ld1 {Vt.<T>}, [Xn]         (no offset, base register only)
        ld1 {Vt.<T>}, [Xn], #bytes  (post-index by element count * element size)
        st1 {Vt.<T>}, [Xn]

The register list is enclosed in curly braces. For single-register transfers,
only one register is listed: {v0.4s}.

Parameters:
- output: pointer to AssemblyOutput
- vt: FPR register ID (32-63) for the vector register
- xn: GPR register ID (0-30) for the base address
- arrangement: data arrangement for element interpretation
@End Reasoning

Process called "emit_neon_load" that takes output as Integer, vt as Integer, xn as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
    Let vec_str be get_neon_reg_name(vt, arrangement)

    Note: Get the base register name (always 64-bit GPR for addresses)
    Let base_buf be Layout.allocate(8)
    Let base_name be ""
    If xn is 31:
        Set base_name to "sp"
    Otherwise:
        Set base_name to "x"
        Let idx_str be StringUtils.integer_to_string(xn)
        Let bb be Layout.allocate(8)
        __store8(bb, 0, 120)  Note: 'x'
        Let ii be 0
        Let ic be __load8(idx_str, ii)
        While ic is not 0:
            __store8(bb, ii plus 1, ic)
            Set ii to ii plus 1
            Set ic to __load8(idx_str, ii)
        End While
        __store8(bb, ii plus 1, 0)
        Set base_name to bb
    End If

    Note: Emit: ld1 {Vt.<T>}, [Xn]
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tld1\t{")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, vec_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "}, [")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, base_name)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, "]")

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "emit_neon_store" that takes output as Integer, vt as Integer, xn as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
    Let vec_str be get_neon_reg_name(vt, arrangement)

    Let base_name be ""
    If xn is 31:
        Set base_name to "sp"
    Otherwise:
        Let bb be Layout.allocate(8)
        __store8(bb, 0, 120)  Note: 'x'
        Let idx_str be StringUtils.integer_to_string(xn)
        Let ii be 0
        Let ic be __load8(idx_str, ii)
        While ic is not 0:
            __store8(bb, ii plus 1, ic)
            Set ii to ii plus 1
            Set ic to __load8(idx_str, ii)
        End While
        __store8(bb, ii plus 1, 0)
        Set base_name to bb
    End If

    Note: Emit: st1 {Vt.<T>}, [Xn]
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tst1\t{")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, vec_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "}, [")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, base_name)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, "]")

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NEON Broadcast Operation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
DUP (duplicate) broadcasts a scalar value from a GPR to all lanes of a NEON register.

Syntax:
  dup Vd.4s, Wn    Note: Broadcast 32-bit GPR to 4 x 32-bit lanes
  dup Vd.2d, Xn    Note: Broadcast 64-bit GPR to 2 x 64-bit lanes
  dup Vd.8h, Wn    Note: Broadcast lower 16 bits to 8 x 16-bit lanes
  dup Vd.16b, Wn   Note: Broadcast lower 8 bits to 16 x 8-bit lanes

The source register size must match the element size:
- 32-bit elements (4S, 2S): use Wn (32-bit GPR name)
- 64-bit elements (2D, 1D): use Xn (64-bit GPR name)
- 16-bit elements (8H, 4H): use Wn (lower 16 bits used)
- 8-bit elements (16B, 8B): use Wn (lower 8 bits used)

Parameters:
- output: pointer to AssemblyOutput
- vd: FPR register ID (32-63) for destination vector
- gpr_src: GPR register ID (0-30) for scalar source value
- arrangement: data arrangement (determines element size and lane count)
@End Reasoning

Process called "emit_neon_broadcast" that takes output as Integer, vd as Integer, gpr_src as Integer, arrangement as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
    Let dest_str be get_neon_reg_name(vd, arrangement)

    Note: Determine GPR name based on element size
    Note: 2D arrangement uses 64-bit Xn, all others use 32-bit Wn
    Let src_name be ""
    If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_2D:
        Note: 64-bit elements: use Xn
        Let buf be Layout.allocate(8)
        __store8(buf, 0, 120)  Note: 'x'
        Let num_str be StringUtils.integer_to_string(gpr_src)
        Let ni be 0
        Let nc be __load8(num_str, ni)
        While nc is not 0:
            __store8(buf, ni plus 1, nc)
            Set ni to ni plus 1
            Set nc to __load8(num_str, ni)
        End While
        __store8(buf, ni plus 1, 0)
        Set src_name to buf
    Otherwise If arrangement is ARRANGEMENT_1D:
        Set buf to Layout.allocate(8)
        __store8(buf, 0, 120)  Note: 'x'
        Set num_str to StringUtils.integer_to_string(gpr_src)
        Set ni to 0
        Set nc to __load8(num_str, ni)
        While nc is not 0:
            __store8(buf, ni plus 1, nc)
            Set ni to ni plus 1
            Set nc to __load8(num_str, ni)
        End While
        __store8(buf, ni plus 1, 0)
        Set src_name to buf
    Otherwise:
        Note: 32-bit, 16-bit, or 8-bit elements: use Wn
        Set buf to Layout.allocate(8)
        __store8(buf, 0, 119)  Note: 'w'
        Set num_str to StringUtils.integer_to_string(gpr_src)
        Set ni to 0
        Set nc to __load8(num_str, ni)
        While nc is not 0:
            __store8(buf, ni plus 1, nc)
            Set ni to ni plus 1
            Set nc to __load8(num_str, ni)
        End While
        __store8(buf, ni plus 1, 0)
        Set src_name to buf
    End If

    Note: Emit: dup Vd.<T>, Xn/Wn
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tdup\t")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
    MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
    MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src_name)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Vector Opcode Dispatch
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Maps LIR vector opcodes (30800-30899) to the appropriate NEON instruction emission.
This function extracts register IDs and arrangement information from the LIR instruction
and calls the corresponding emit function.

LIR vector instruction layout:
  [0]  opcode (30800-30899)
  [8]  result operand (destination Vd register)
  [16] operand1 (source Vn register)
  [24] operand2 (source Vm register or address Xn for load/store)
  [32] operand3 (arrangement specifier or GPR source for broadcast)

The arrangement is stored in the instruction's metadata field at offset 32 as an
integer matching the ARRANGEMENT_* constants.

Returns 1 on success, 0 on unknown opcode or error.
@End Reasoning

Process called "map_lir_vector_op" that takes output as Integer, instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be __load(instruction, 0)

    Note: Extract register IDs
    Let result_ptr be __load(instruction, 8)
    Let op1_ptr be __load(instruction, 16)
    Let op2_ptr be __load(instruction, 24)

    Let vd be 32  Note: Default to V0
    Let vn be 32
    Let vm be 32

    If result_ptr is not 0:
        Let res_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
        If res_type is 1:
            Set vd to __load(result_ptr, 8)
        End If
    End If

    If op1_ptr is not 0:
        Let op1_type be __load(op1_ptr, 0)
        If op1_type is 1:
            Set vn to __load(op1_ptr, 8)
        End If
    End If

    If op2_ptr is not 0:
        Let op2_type be __load(op2_ptr, 0)
        If op2_type is 1:
            Set vm to __load(op2_ptr, 8)
        End If
    End If

    Note: Read arrangement from instruction metadata at offset 32
    Let arrangement be __load(instruction, 32)
    Note: Validate arrangement range
    If arrangement is less than 0:
        Set arrangement to ARRANGEMENT_4S
    End If
    If arrangement is greater than 7:
        Set arrangement to ARRANGEMENT_4S
    End If

    Note: Dispatch based on opcode
    If opcode is LIR_VADD from LIR:
        Return emit_neon_add(output, vd, vn, vm, arrangement)
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VSUB from LIR:
        Return emit_neon_sub(output, vd, vn, vm, arrangement)
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VMUL from LIR:
        Return emit_neon_mul(output, vd, vn, vm, arrangement)
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VAND from LIR:
        Return emit_neon_and(output, vd, vn, vm, arrangement)
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VOR from LIR:
        Return emit_neon_or(output, vd, vn, vm, arrangement)
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VXOR from LIR:
        Return emit_neon_xor(output, vd, vn, vm, arrangement)
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VLOAD from LIR:
        Note: For vector load, op1 is the base address register (GPR)
        Let base_reg be 0
        If op1_ptr is not 0:
            Set op1_type to __load(op1_ptr, 0)
            If op1_type is 1:
                Set base_reg to __load(op1_ptr, 8)
            End If
        End If
        Return emit_neon_load(output, vd, base_reg, arrangement)
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VSTORE from LIR:
        Note: For vector store, result is the source vector, op1 is the base address
        Set base_reg to 0
        If op1_ptr is not 0:
            Set op1_type to __load(op1_ptr, 0)
            If op1_type is 1:
                Set base_reg to __load(op1_ptr, 8)
            End If
        End If
        Return emit_neon_store(output, vd, base_reg, arrangement)
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VBROADCAST from LIR:
        Note: For broadcast, op1 is the GPR source register
        Let gpr_src be 0
        If op1_ptr is not 0:
            Set op1_type to __load(op1_ptr, 0)
            If op1_type is 1:
                Set gpr_src to __load(op1_ptr, 8)
            End If
        End If
        Return emit_neon_broadcast(output, vd, gpr_src, arrangement)
    End If

    Note: Floating-point NEON operations
    If opcode is LIR_VFADD from LIR:
        Note: fadd Vd.<T>, Vn.<T>, Vm.<T>
        Let section be MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
        Let dest_str be get_neon_reg_name(vd, arrangement)
        Let src1_str be get_neon_reg_name(vn, arrangement)
        Let src2_str be get_neon_reg_name(vm, arrangement)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tfadd\t")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VFSUB from LIR:
        Set section to MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
        Set dest_str to get_neon_reg_name(vd, arrangement)
        Set src1_str to get_neon_reg_name(vn, arrangement)
        Set src2_str to get_neon_reg_name(vm, arrangement)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tfsub\t")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VFMUL from LIR:
        Set section to MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
        Set dest_str to get_neon_reg_name(vd, arrangement)
        Set src1_str to get_neon_reg_name(vn, arrangement)
        Set src2_str to get_neon_reg_name(vm, arrangement)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tfmul\t")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is LIR_VFDIV from LIR:
        Set section to MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT
        Set dest_str to get_neon_reg_name(vd, arrangement)
        Set src1_str to get_neon_reg_name(vn, arrangement)
        Set src2_str to get_neon_reg_name(vm, arrangement)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, "\tfdiv\t")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, dest_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, src1_str)
        MachineCode.asm_emit_to_section(output, section, ", ")
        MachineCode.asm_emit_line(output, section, src2_str)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Unknown vector opcode
    Return 0
End Process
